    "reasoning": "First, find the unique real root $ r $ of $ Q'(x) $. Since $ Q(x) = x^2 + 2x + 3 $, its derivative is $ Q'(x) = 2x + 2 $, which has a root at $ x = -1 $. Compute $ Q(-1) = (-1)^2 + 2(-1) + 3 = 2 $, so $ k = Q(r) - 1 = 2 - 1 = 1 $. The problem asks whether there exists an irrational $ \alpha > 1 $ such that $ \lfloor \alpha^n \rfloor \equiv 0 \pmod{2017} $ for all integers $ n \geq 1 $.

For $ n = 1 $, $ \lfloor \alpha \rfloor $ must be divisible by 2017, so $ \alpha \in [2017, 2018) $. For $ n = 2 $, $ \lfloor \alpha^2 \rfloor $ must also be divisible by 2017. However, analyzing the binomial expansion of $ (2017 + \epsilon)^n $ for small $ \epsilon > 0 $, the term $ n \cdot 2017^{n-1} \epsilon $ grows with $ n $. For any fixed $ \epsilon > 0 $, there exists some $ n $ where $ n \cdot 2017^{n-1} \epsilon > 1 $, causing $ \lfloor \alpha^n \rfloor $ to exceed $ 2017^n $ by at least 1, making $ \lfloor \alpha^n \rfloor \not\equiv 0 \pmod{2017} $. 

If $ \alpha < 2017 $, $ \lfloor \alpha \rfloor < 2017 $, so $ \lfloor \alpha \rfloor \not\equiv 0 \pmod{2017} $, failing for $ n = 1 $. The only case where $ \lfloor \alpha^n \rfloor \equiv 0 \pmod{2017} $ for all $ n $ is $ \alpha = 2017 $, but it is rational. Thus, no irrational $ \alpha > 1 $ satisfies the condition.",
